07658nam a22010215i 9783110716962DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107169627 a10.1515/97831107169622doi  a(DE-B1597)567080  a(OCoLC)1226679555  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aSymbolism 2020 :bAn International Annual of Critical Aesthetics /ced. by Rüdiger Ahrens, Florian Klaeger, Klaus Stierstorfer. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VIII, 260 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSymbolism : An International Annual of Critical Aesthetics ,x1528-3623 ;v2000tFrontmatter -- tForeword from the Editors -- tContents -- tSpecial Focus: Symbols of the Future. The Future of Symbolism -- tIntroduction: Symbols of the Future. The Future of Symbolism -- tSymbol’s Risks: A Note on the Interrelationship of Art and the Use of Symbols -- t‘Symbolic Futures’ as Investment -- tOn the Future Role of Symbols in Environmental Modelling -- tThe Symbolization of the Female Body in Western Culture from Ancient Greece to the Transmodern Period -- tGenre and Utopia, or 48 Hrs. for the Future: Perspectives in Media Aesthetics -- tThe Past Is Immutable: Technology’s Symbolism and the Future in Black Mirror -- t“Players and painted stage”: Symbolizing the Future in Shaw’s Back to Methuselah -- tHerzlian Matrix: Theme Parks, Promised Lands, and Simulacra -- tReading the Future through the Past: Symbolism in Amitav Ghosh’s Anthropogenic Fiction -- tThe Cyborg, Symbol of the Evolution of the Human, or The Human of the Future -- t“An ocean of thought”: AI, Robots, and Ian McEwan’s Machines Like Me and People Like You (2019) -- tBook Reviews -- tSarah C. Bishop. Undocumented Storytellers: Narrating the Immigrant Rights Movement -- tSandra Dinter. Childhood in the Contemporary English Novel -- tJohannes Riquet. The Aesthetics of Island Space: Perception, Ideology, Geopoetics -- tLyndsey Stonebridge. Placeless People: Writing, Rights, and Refugees -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis special anniversary volume of Symbolism explores the nexus between symbolic signification and the future from an interdisciplinary perspective. How, contributors ask, has the future been variously rendered in symbolic terms? How do symbols and symbolic reference shape our ideas of the future? To what extent are symbols constitutive of futures, and to what extent do they restrain communication about what is possible and the imagination of fundamental change? Moreover, how have symbolic practices shaped not only artistic representations of the future, but also scientific attempts at forecasting and modelling it? What, then, is the relevance of symbolism for negotiations of the future in cultural and academic production? In essays ranging from literary and film studies to the philosophy of art and ecological modelling, the volume seeks to lay groundwork in theorizing and historicising ‘symbols of the future’ as much as ‘the future of symbolism’.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023)  aSymbol.  afutures studies.  aliterary form.  asymbolism.1 aAhrens, Rüdiger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBatzke, Ina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBharucha, Nilufer E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkhard, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpi, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Ja